[2
Date: Sat, 22 Jan 2000 13:25:16 EST
From: T. J. O'Neil <Tjon1950@aol.com>

That would make efforts to bio-engineer oral vaccines into common
foodstuffs all the more important as a contribution to global health---the
economic disincentives to reporting of infectious diseases are perverse,
but unavoidable and understandable in a free-trade-oriented world.
However, if the contribution to world health of the developed-world's
agro-businesses could be made "enlightened self-interest" through subsidies
to designing in the antibody-inducing proteins and glycoproteins, I think
we would have a win-win situation. Your thoughts?
--
T.J. O'Neil, MD, FACP
e-mail: Tjon1950@aol.com
[We will never know "your thoughts" because we are cutting this string. I
cannot resist commenting that although Dr. O'Neil is correct in saying that
"economic disincentives to reporting of infectious diseases are perverse" I
cannot agree that they are unavoidable or understandable. If all that
matters in this world is money, I am in the wrong world. - Mod.CHC
